        "id": 258473,
        "name": "Bartlomiej Szulik",
        "username": "Bart1337",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/bart1337/{size}/50180_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-01-09T14:43:08.356Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Dear Signal Team,</p>\n<p>I’d like to suggest a new feature for group chats that could improve the user experience and provide more flexibility in managing group dynamics. Currently, Signal allows for two roles in group chats: administrators and regular participants. I propose adding a third role: <strong>Read-Only Participants</strong>.</p>\n<p>Here’s how the roles could function:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Administrators: Full control over group settings and the ability to manage participants.</li>\n<li>Regular Participants: Can read, send messages, and participate fully in group discussions.</li>\n<li>Read-Only Participants: Can only view messages in the chat but cannot send messages or react to posts. They could still receive updates and announcements made by the group.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This feature would be especially useful for scenarios such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Educational groups where only teachers or moderators post updates, and students or members are restricted to reading the content.</li>\n<li>Large announcement groups where interaction needs to be limited to maintain focus on official communication.</li>\n<li>Temporary roles for new members or observers who may not need to contribute actively.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I believe this enhancement aligns with Signal’s goal of providing private and efficient communication while empowering group admins with more control.</p>\n<p>Thank you for considering this idea. I appreciate all the work you do to keep Signal innovative and user-friendly.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 3,
        "updated_at": "2025-01-09T14:43:14.165Z",
